The paper deals with algorithms for approximating the singular value spectrum of a matrix, which is a fundamental task in many areas of computer science and mathematics. The paper uses tools from stochastic trace estimation, polynomial approximation, and fast system solvers, which are commonly used in numerical analysis and optimization (cs.NA). The paper also discusses the complexity of spectrum approximation in relation to fast matrix multiplication, which is a central problem in theoretical computer science (cs.IT). The paper's applications to computing matrix norms and effective resistances in graphs suggest that it belongs to the categories of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), and machine learning (cs.LG).
